latestIgtvVideos.title: How to treat Melasma
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Common causes of Melasma:
1. Genetic susceptibility 
2. Hormonal fluctuations (like in PCOS, pregnancy, menopause, using contraceptive pills)
3. Excessive sun exposure and not using a sunscreen 

Treatment:

Treating existing lesions: 
1. Using Retinol, tretinoin, kojic acid, tranexamic acid creams 
2. In clinic treatments: Chemical peels, prp, laser treatments 

Continuous care for preventing recurrence:
1. Regular use of sunscreen (preferably tinted)
2. Vitamin c/ Niacinamide/ Glutathione serum
3. OTC Retinol creams

latestPosts.caption:
All your cuticle oils are going to fail in front of this!
Here is the routine you need to follow:

Daily:
Just keep a tub of Vaseline petroleum jelly on you bedside and massage your nails and cuticles daily at night before bed.

Weekly Exfoliation (because getting rid of the excess cuticles and dead skin is necessary)

Step 1: clean your hands with soap

Step 2: Apply a drop of chemical cuticle exfoliater on each nail (Sally Hansen cuticle remover is what I use). Make sure to cover the cuticle, sides of the nails and even inside the nails. Let it stay for 2 minutes and then wash off with plain water 

Step 3: Scrub your hands. Here is the DIY scrub that I use:
1 tbsp oatmeal powder
1 tsp fine ground coffee beans
1 tbsp ground white sugar
1 tsp honey 
1 tbsp coconut oil 
1 tbsp shower gel (can use more if needed to bind everything together)

Step 4: Rinse and apply a thick moisturiser or Vaseline petroleum jelly!

This has been my routine since a few months now. And it really eliminates the need for fake nails and gel manicures for me. 

You can use the same products and same process for your feet as well💛✨

1. Carbon facial
👉🏻Works best for for oily, acne prone, pigmented skin
👉🏻No down time. Can be done even 1-2 days before an event 
👉🏻Expect reduction in redness and inflammation within a couple of hours. Skin feels more balanced , controls excess oil secretion, hence results in temporary reduction in pore visibility 
👉🏻Reduction is uneven skin tone, freckles, hyperpigmentation after 2-3 sessions
👉🏻Repeat every 30-45 days for best results 

2. Retinol Peel
👉🏻Works best to control acne and treat acne spots. 
👉🏻Has a down time of 3-7 days
👉🏻Expect slight irritation and peeling for the first 2-3 days
👉🏻Repeat every 45-50 days for best results 

3. Microneedling 
👉🏻Works best for anti-aging, fine lines, mild superficial acne scars
👉🏻Has a down time of 2-4 days
👉🏻Expect mild irritation, redness for the first 12-24 hours. 
👉🏻Skin begins to look more radiant, plump, and fine lines look reduced within 1 week post treatment 
👉🏻Repeat every 2 months for best results 

4. & 5. Hydra facial 
👉🏻Works best for dry skin or for a quick hydration and glow before an event.
👉🏻Results are better and more lasting when combined with a Lactic Acid Chemical Peel
👉🏻No downtime 
👉🏻Repeat every month for best results

✨ Cleared your acne but those stubborn marks just won’t fade? You’re not alone—and yes, there is a fix.

Here are 3 doctor-backed steps to finally fade post-acne pigmentation and reclaim your glow:
🌱 A daily plant protein + blueberry smoothie (hello, antioxidant boost!)
🌞 Switch to tinted sunscreen + brightening actives in your AM routine
🌙 Use a gentle, beginner-friendly retinoid at night to smooth and renew

I’ve broken it all down in this reel—watch till the end for product recommendations that actually work (including my go-to @rasluxuryoils picks!).

📌 Save this routine for later & share it with someone battling acne scars!

To get your hands on these products head to their website or Nykaa today ✨

#rasluxuryskincare #farmtoface

1. Detox water is just cherry 🍒 on the cake. The cake 🎂 needs the whole recipe- your daily meals, your sleep, your exercise routine, your supplements.
2. It’s the worst. Proportion change, listening to your body for signs of hunger and fullness, disconnect from emotional eating, not eating just out of boredom is what works. Always NUTRITION >> amount of CALORIES 

3. Picking few good products targeted to your concerns >> layering all the actives you just bought. I follow the rule of two. No more than 2 active ingredients in your skincare routine. One active you use in the morning, one at night. If needed, 1 exfoliant once a week. That’s it!

4. Non-comedogenic products is more like half science for me. Even products that have some comedogenic ingredients can still work well for acne prone skin. Skincare product is a combination of all ingredients it is made of. If it has a comedogenic ingredient, it will almost always have another ingredient to balance its effect. Moreover, label of non-comedogenic doesn’t guarantee safety for acne prone skin. 
5. I have always found them more drying than hydrating. I cannot prove it using science but to my logical thinking, 1. spraying mineral rich water on your face will only draw out moisture from your skin. 2. It will also create a damp environment and make it easier for bacterial overgrowth. Using mist on cleansed face and using moisturiser on top of it is great!!! But using a mist 10 times a day thinking it will be hydrating is not something that works according to me. U could be wrong (but you will have to argue and prove me wrong)

6. Expensive products feel luxurious and make you enjoy the process of doing your skincare. But it doesn’t necessarily guarantee a good product. I have experienced so many high end, pricey and heavily marketed products fail tremendously.

7. This needs no explanation. It’s straight fact. I created a reel explaining this a while back. Feel free to scroll down my profile to watch it:))

Feel free to reason with me in the comments if you feel anything I stated is not right.

latestPosts.caption: It’s really not that difficult. Let me tell you from experience, all other shortcuts (ozempic, Carnitine, etc) eventually fail. What stays with you are your healthy habits.

Here is the AI prompt that you guys can copy, paste and use: 

Please analyze the safety and suitability of the following [product typel ingredients for my [skin/hair typel. I have Ispecific concerns, e.gu_eily,_ sensitive scalp or acne-prone skin, so let me know if this product is a good fit for my routine. Also, suggest alternative products available in India that may work better for my needs. Here is the ingredient list: [Paste ingredients here]

I almost did not upload this reel. Because whenever I talk about supplements, you guys think that it's a cheat code and try to copy and take whatever I am taking. 
🔥For a little context, I for example do not take a protein supplement. Why? Because I am a non-vegetarian and my diet includes fish/chicken/mutton daily. But if you are a vegetarian, protein and B-complex become more essential for you compared to all the supplements I am talking about here. 
🔥Another question you need to ask yourself before choosing your supplements is--> Can I get this nutrition from my diet? Take the supplement only if the answer is No. For example for me- Can I take vitamin C from my diet? The answer is yes. So I do not take a vitamin C supplement. 
🔥Lastly if you need my help in choosing the supplements and taking care of your general well being, please reach out to my team at 9667066616.
